  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn1" class="fn" href="#_ftnref1" id="_ftn1">[1]</a> Respondent is currently
  ineligible to practice law based upon his failure to pay his 2005 bar dues and disciplinary assessment fee.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn2" class="fn" href="#_ftnref2" id="_ftn2">[2]</a> Rule 1.8(h) in effect at the
  time of misconduct stated:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">"(h)  A lawyer shall not make an agreement prospectively limiting the lawyer's liability to
    a client for   malpractice unless permitted by law and the client is independently represented in making the
    agreement, or settle a claim for such liability with an unrepresented client or former client without   first
    advising that person in writing that independent representation is appropriate in connection therewith."</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext">  Rule 8.4 (a)(c) stated that:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">  " It is professional misconduct for a lawyer to:</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">(a) Violate or attempt to violate the Rules of Professional Conduct, knowingly assist or
    induce another to do so, or do so through the acts of another; . . .</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">(c) Engage in conduct involving dishonesty, fraud, deceit or misrepresentation."</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn3" class="fn" href="#_ftnref3" id="_ftn3">[3]</a> The record in this matter
  indicates that the checks given to Mr. Steptoe were actually dated February 22, 2000 and June 10, 2000.  They were
  cashed by Mr. Steptoe on February 23, 2000 and July 10, 2000, respectively.  The settlement statements are dated
  February 22, 2000 and July 10, 2000, respectively.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn4" class="fn" href="#_ftnref4" id="_ftn4">[4]</a> Standard 4.33 states: 
  "Reprimand is generally appropriate when a lawyer is negligent in determining whether the representation of a client
  may be materially affected by the lawyer's own interest, or whether the representation will adversely affect another
  client, and causes injury or potential injury to the client."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn5" class="fn" href="#_ftnref5" id="_ftn5">[5]</a> Respondent was admitted to the
  practice of law in Louisiana on April 22, 1977.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn6" class="fn" href="#_ftnref6" id="_ftn6">[6]</a> In 1999, Respondent was
  sanctioned with diversion based upon his lack of diligence and neglect of a legal matter.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn7" class="fn" href="#_ftnref7" id="_ftn7">[7]</a> The factual findings made by
  the committee consist only of the statement "[t]here being no response from Respondent[,] the Formal Charges are
