  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn9" class="fn" href="#_ftnref9" id="_ftn9">[9]</a> In his letter of April 6,
  1999, the Respondent writes to Mr. Steptoe and states:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">"Dear Mr. Steptoe:</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">  Thank you for meeting with me today.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">This is to confirm our conversation where I advised you that your workers' compensation  
    case had prescribed.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">  Sincerely,</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">  Michael K. Boudreaux"</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><i>See</i> ODC Exhibit 11.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn10" class="fn" href="#_ftnref10" id="_ftn10">[10]</a> The formal charges address
  this issue by quoting the language of the settlement sheet sent with both the February 22, 2000 and the July 10, 2000
  payments.  In the formal charges, ODC asserts that this language  reads:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">  "This is to verify that I received $10,000.00 (ten thousand and no/100 dollars) on July
    10, 2000 from Michael K. Boudreaux as partial settlement of my claim from my workers' compensation case.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">  /<u>s</u>/</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">  Ralph Steptoe"</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext">ODC Exhibit 2 shows that the same language was used in the settlement sheet sent with the
  February 22, 2000 payment, except the date on that settlement sheet sent read February 22, 2000.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">ODC further asserts in the formal charges that "Boudreaux attempted to settle a claim for
  malpractice by the payment of $20,000.00."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">In his complaint, Mr. Steptoe states that " . . . the last time I [saw Respondent] was 2000
  and 2001.  I was supposed to get [a] settlement from 1986 to 2002, I should have [a] settlement counted plus
  $109,912.00.  But he never act[ed] [to] do it for me.  I know that he already got [a] settlement before . . . I
  didn't know [the] arrangement.  . . . We never [withdrew] money from worker compensation [for] my case."  <i>See</i>
  ODC Exhibit 1.   In his letters written to ODC during the investigation of this matter, it appears that Mr. Steptoe
  believed that the settlement amounts paid by Respondent on February 22, 2000 and July 10, 2000 were from Respondent's
  personal funds, but that additional funds were due from the worker's compensation insurer.  <i>See</i> ODC Exhibits 3
  and 4.  As explained above, because Mr. Steptoe's claim had been abandoned, no settlement funds were due from the
  worker's compensation insurer.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn11" class="fn" href="#_ftnref11" id="_ftn11">[11]</a> The committee noted
  that:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">  "Respondent further testified that the $20,000.00 payment to Complainant was based upon a
    combination of Social Security and Worker's Compensation payments that Complainant received for 62 weeks. 
    Respondent contended that for 458 weeks the Complainant received $2,000.00 less per year when worker's compensation
    discontinued the payments. Respondent calculated the Complainant's total loss at $17,600.00 and therefore he
    settled with the Complainant for $20,000.00. </p>

    <p class="footnotetext">The Committee finds that Respondent's conduct appeared to be generally geared towards
    making the client whole and to provide restitution which is a mitigating factor.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">Hrg. Comm. Rpt., p. 4.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext">In his sworn statement, the Respondent explained that he reached the $20,000.00 amount by
  determining what Mr. Steptoe would have been paid for his worker's compensation over the course of the ten year
  period that he was entitled to receive the benefits.  Respondent testified that this amount came to "a little over
  $17,000.00."  Respondent also added to that figure an amount to compensate Mr. Steptoe for any medical expenses he
  might have had and arrived at the $20,000.00 figure.  ODC Exhibit 10, Sworn Statement of Respondent, pp. 27-29. </p>

  <p class="footnotetext">In his letter dated February 12, 2004 in which Respondent responds to Mr. Steptoe's complaint
  to ODC, he further explains the settlement figure as follows:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">  "Prior to his injury, Mr. Steptoe earned approximately $9,900.00 per year.  He received
    Worker's Compensation payment of $127 a week for 62 weeks, totaling $7762.  This $127 per week plus Social Security
    Disability gave him an income of $7920 per year which was the maximum 80% of his pre-injury income.  When Worker's
    Comp stopped paying him he qualified for additional Social Security Benefits and began receiving approximately $500
    per month in disability payments.  This totaled approximately $6,000 per year which he continued to receive
    throughout the duration of his claim period.  This amount was about $2000 less than the $7920 maximum he could have
    received from a combination of Social Security and Worker's Compensation payments.  Since he received both Social
    Security and Worker's Compensation payments for 62 weeks that left 458 weeks (8.8 years) in which he received
    $2,000 less per year that he would have received if both Social Security and Worker's Comp had been paying, or
    approximately $17,600 less over the 458 week period.  If Mr. Steptoe had received a Worker's Comp settlement,
    Social Security would have reduced or eliminated its payments by offsetting the settlement against its payments
    until the Worker's Comp settlement had been "used up" against the Social Security benefits. In the alternative,
    Worker's Comp would have been entitled to offset the Social Security Payments received by Mr. Steptoe, leaving the
    same $17,600."</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><i>See</i> ODC Exhibit 2.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn12" class="fn" href="#_ftnref12" id="_ftn12">[12]</a> Respondent had received a
  prior two and one half year suspension, formal private reprimand and admonition.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a name="_ftn13" class="fn" href="#_ftnref13" id="_ftn13">[13]</a> Respondent had received an
  admonition for failure to cooperate.</p>
